All three cases work as expected. Here's the final program:

```csharp
// Program.cs — targets net11.0
using System.Text.Json;
using System.Text.Json.Serialization;
using System.Text.Json.Serialization.Metadata;

var options = new JsonSerializerOptions(JsonSerializerDefaults.Web)
{
    TypeInfoResolver = new DefaultJsonTypeInfoResolver()
};

// 1) GetTypeInfo<T>() — strongly-typed metadata, no cast
JsonTypeInfo<Person> personInfo = options.GetTypeInfo<Person>();
string json = JsonSerializer.Serialize(new Person("Alice", 42), personInfo);

// 2) TryGetTypeInfo<T>() — probe without throwing
var limited = new JsonSerializerOptions { TypeInfoResolver = LimitedContext.Default };

if (limited.TryGetTypeInfo<Order>(out JsonTypeInfo<Order>? orderInfo))
    Console.WriteLine($"Found: {orderInfo!.Type.Name}");
else
    Console.WriteLine("Not available — no exception thrown");
```

**Key APIs (new in .NET 11):**

| Method | Returns | Throws if missing? |
|--------|---------|-------------------|
| `options.GetTypeInfo<T>()` | `JsonTypeInfo<T>` | Yes |
| `options.TryGetTypeInfo<T>(out …)` | `bool` | No |

Use `GetTypeInfo<T>()` when you *know* metadata exists; use `TryGetTypeInfo<T>()` to branch safely without try/catch.
